": "https", "video_ext": "mp4", "audio_ext": "none", "abr": 0, "vbr": 1742.757, "resolution": "1080x1920", "aspect_ratio": 0.56, "filesize_approx": 13509634, "http_headers": {"User-Agent": "Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/143.0.0.0 Safari/537.36", "Accept": "text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8", "Accept-Language": "en-us,en;q=0.5", "Sec-Fetch-Mode": "navigate", "Referer": "https://www.instagram.com/"}, "format": "dash-1345320200966011v - 1080x1920 (DASH video)"}], "title": "Video by bilawal.ai", "description": "Comment '4D' to get the full video. A week after building WorldView, the Iran strikes kicked off and I realized I was sitting on the perfect infrastructure to monitor it in real time.\n\nDeployed an AI agent swarm to capture every open source signal before the caches cleared. What came back is a full 4D reconstruction of Operation Epic Fury — scrubable, replayable, minute by minute on a 3D globe:\n\n→ Satellite overpasses lining up before the first strike\n→ Commercial flights scattering as no-fly zones cascade across the Gulf\n→ Ships rerouting through chokepoints in real time\n→ The full retaliatory response captured from multiple data layers\n\nIt started as a weekend project. A personal geospatial command center just for fun. Turns out the best time to have the tool is before you need it.\n\nOpen source intelligence is undefeated. Dropping WorldView in April — this is just the beginning.\n\n#ai #osint #3d #futuretech #aviation", "duration": 62.015, "timestamp": 1772989390, "uploader_id": "18039316", "uploader": "Bilawal Sidhu", "channel": "bilawal.ai", "like_count": 17927, "comment_count": 2017, "comments": [{"author": "1234mrwick", "author_id": "31038642956", "id": "17878556250458828", "text": "4d", "timestamp": 1779990420}, {"author": "oobef3", "author_id": "75161213256", "id": "17926152138341126", "text": "4D", "timestamp": 1779949874}, {"author": "azizm.duo", "author_i